{
  "texts": [
    "In the early stages, studies of dynamical processes on higherorder networks focused on understanding how the nature of the transitions changes by tuning the number and strength of higher-order interactions.",
    "Firstly, models of social contagion in homogeneous systems with uncorrelated higher-order interactions were considered.",
    "It was found that discontinuous transitions occur exclusively when the strength of higher-order interactions exceeds a critical threshold 25, 27, 28.",
    "However, subsequent research [38] [39] [40] revealed that the strength of the interactions is not the sole determinant of behavioral changes in social systems.",
    "Remarkable examples include the dynamical influence of heterogeneity in the node participation within groups (analyzed through group size distributions) 40, and the role of giant higher-order components (HOC) 41 in the stability of social contagion processes, even in absence of pairwise interactions 42."
  ]
}